Quick start
===========

Libcwd requires CMake, which can be used to configure, build, *and* install libcwd.

The native target to link with is `Libcwd::cwd`, made available with a
`find_package(libcwd CONFIG)`, however if you also use `cwds` then that is dragged
in as dependency and don't need that `find_package` and you only need to link with
`AICxx::cwds`, or rather use `${AICXX_OBJECTS_LIST}`:

Canonical documentation: https://github.com/CarloWood/cwds#adding-the-cwds-submodule-to-a-project

It is highly recommended to use gitache to get/configure/compile libcwd,
and you very likely want to use the git submodule `cwds` too (which in turn requires `cmake-aicxx`).

gitache
-------

Libcwd installs one library, named libcwd, with thread support always enabled.
Use `set(GITACHE_PACKAGES libcwd)`. This is also covered by the cwds documentation, linked above.

Only if you can't or do not want to use gitache, then the following two paragraphs apply.

git
---

If you obtained the source code from git, then first run `./autogen.sh`
to initialize/update the required git submodules and print the CMake
commands for a local build.

cmake
-----

# For example,
REPOROOT="$PWD"                 # The root of the project.
BUILDDIR="$REPOROOT-build"      # Do an out-of-source build.
CMAKE_CONFIG="Debug"            # Or Release, etc.
PREFIX="/usr/local"

# Configure
cmake -DCMAKE_INSTALL_PREFIX="$PREFIX" -S "$REPOROOT" -B "$BUILDDIR" -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE="$CMAKE_CONFIG" -DCMAKE_MESSAGE_LOG_LEVEL=DEBUG
# Build
cmake --build "$BUILDDIR"
cmake --build "$BUILDDIR" --target doc  # Generate documentation (afterwards open file://$BUILDDIR/doc/index.html).
# Install
sudo cmake --install "$BUILDDIR" --config "$CMAKE_CONFIG" --prefix "$PREFIX" --parallel $(nproc)

Options
=======

cmake
-----

The following boolean variables can be set to ON or OFF on the command line,

   EnableGlibCxxDebug      : Compile libcwd with -D_GLIBCXX_DEBUG.
                             See https://gcc.gnu.org/onlinedocs/libstdc++/manual/debug_mode_using.html#debug_mode.using.mode
   EnableLibcwdLocation    : Enable the ability to lookup source file and line
                             number, you might need this on a non-ELF system.
   EnableBuildTesting      : Compile the CTest testsuite.
(you do not want to use these):
   EnableLibcwdDebug       : Enable debugging of libcwd itself.
   EnableLibcwdDebugOutput : Enable debug output of EnableLibcwdDebug.
   EnableLibcwdDebugt      : Enable debugging of threading debugging code in libcwd itself.

When running `cmake --log-level=STATUS` each option and its value is printed (unless
forced to OFF); often a value is forced or has a default. Recommended is to only set
an option if you're not happy with the default.

Trouble
=======

If you run into problems, mail carlo@alinoe.com (include as many details as possible).
Please use a very clear subject so that I can see it isn't spam in under 0.2 seconds.
